T1  - The Choice of Strategic Alternatives Under Increasing Regulation in High Technology Companies
AU  - Birnbaum, Philip H.
Y1  - 1984/09/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256041
DO  - 10.5465/256041
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 489
EP  - 510
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The strategic response of U.S. high technology companies in the medical X-ray manufacturing industry to increased governmental regulations from 1962 to 1977 is examined. Results suggest that regulations increase consumer and competitor uncertainty, with the consequence that firms select less risky strategies and decrease the riskier new product invention strategy. Larger firms reduce inventions less than smaller firms.
AB  - The strategic response of U.S. high technology companies in the medical X-ray manufacturing industry to increased governmental regulations from 1962 to 1977 is examined. Results suggest that regulations increase consumer and competitor uncertainty, with the consequence that firms select less risky strategies and decrease the riskier new product invention strategy. Larger firms reduce inventions less than smaller firms.
