T1  - Administration Size and Organization Size: An Examination of the Lag Structure
AU  - Cullen, John B.
AU  - Baker, Douglas D.
Y1  - 1984/09/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256051
DO  - 10.5465/256051
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 644
EP  - 653
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article provides information on a study pertaining to the lag structure in the relationship between organization size and administration size. The major benefit attributed to the use of longitudinal data for the study of organizational size and administration is the increased understanding of causal processes. The study concludes that appropriate single time lags for longitudinal studies of organizational properties may not be applicable to an entire organizational sample even when that sample is homogeneous in terms of type. Experts say important factors to be considered in future research on organization size and administration size are the types of administrative personnel studied.
AB  - The article provides information on a study pertaining to the lag structure in the relationship between organization size and administration size. The major benefit attributed to the use of longitudinal data for the study of organizational size and administration is the increased understanding of causal processes. The study concludes that appropriate single time lags for longitudinal studies of organizational properties may not be applicable to an entire organizational sample even when that sample is homogeneous in terms of type. Experts say important factors to be considered in future research on organization size and administration size are the types of administrative personnel studied.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256051
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256051
Y2  - 2026/04/24
