TY  - JOUR
T1  - Research Notes. Follower Attitudes Toward Women And Judgments Concerning Performance By Female And Male Leaders
AU  - Adams, Jerome
AU  - Rice, Robert W.
AU  - Instone, Debra
Y1  - 1984/09/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256050
DO  - 10.5465/256050
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 636
EP  - 643
VL  - 27
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The article presents a study pertaining to the attitudes of male cadets toward their female leaders. The study utilized the Army Research Institute's attitudes toward women in the military scale (ARIAWS). The subjects were U.S. Military Academy cadets in leader and trainee roles at Cadet Basic Training and Cadet Field Training. The study results were compared with the results from a similar study conducted at West Point. Researchers discovered that male cadet attitudes about their female leaders were favorably influenced by the leader's performance, negating the negative sex-role stereotypes.
AB  - The article presents a study pertaining to the attitudes of male cadets toward their female leaders. The study utilized the Army Research Institute's attitudes toward women in the military scale (ARIAWS). The subjects were U.S. Military Academy cadets in leader and trainee roles at Cadet Basic Training and Cadet Field Training. The study results were compared with the results from a similar study conducted at West Point. Researchers discovered that male cadet attitudes about their female leaders were favorably influenced by the leader's performance, negating the negative sex-role stereotypes.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256050
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256050
Y2  - 2026/04/24
